# Reply Memory Feature

## Overview

The reply memory system exists to improve future draft replies from prior user corrections.

It should do two jobs:

- act as a lightweight runtime corrective layer for drafting
- automatically build useful knowledge for users who do not maintain a manual knowledge base

The system should not treat all learned data the same way.
Some learned items are always-on writing preferences.
Some are conditional facts or procedures.
Some are raw evidence that should be kept for analysis and eval generation, but not injected directly into prompts.

## Core Principles

### Atomic Memories

Each memory should be one atomic fragment in a single canonical `content` field.

Do not split a memory across `title + content`.
The memory itself should already be a prompt-ready instruction or fact.

### Memory Types

We should move toward these conceptual types:

- `fact`
  - durable business knowledge, routing rules, pricing, policies
- `preference`
  - writing style, formatting, greeting/sign-off habits
- `procedure`
  - how to handle a recurring class of replies
- raw evidence
  - draft/send correction signals used for analysis, consolidation, and evals

### Small Prompt Footprint

The drafting prompt should stay small.

- style/preferences should be compact and mostly always-on
- facts/procedures should be selected conditionally
- raw evidence should usually stay out of the prompt

## Retrieval Model

### Main Drafter

The main drafting path should receive:

- manual writing style
- learned style profile
- a small selected set of relevant facts/procedures

It should not rely on a large memory dump.

### Subagent

For subagents, progressive disclosure is acceptable because extra hops are fine.

The preferred pattern is:

1. give the subagent a compact tag index
2. ask which tags it wants to expand
3. expand only those sections
4. optionally allow a free-form search pass
5. ask the subagent to extract the relevant items

This is a CAG-style memory selector for subagents, not for the main drafter.

### Tag Index

Tags should be controlled and simple.
The tags themselves are the short summary.
We do not need extra prose summaries per tag at first.

Good tag categories:

- kind: fact / preference / procedure
- scope: global / sender / domain / topic
- topic: pricing / billing / scheduling / support / intros / logistics / etc.
- confidence: high / medium / low
- state: active / conflicted / stale

Free-form search can be layered on top to help the subagent find relevant areas when tags are not enough.

## Knowledge Base Relationship

Most users do not have a manual knowledge base.

The reply memory system can serve as an automatic KB for those users.

That means:

- `fact` and `procedure` items are effectively auto-KB entries
- `preference` items are user-specific drafting bias
- raw evidence is the learning substrate that feeds both

The system should not assume manual KB coverage.

## Evidence and Retention

Raw draft/send evidence is useful for:

- improving prompts
- building evals
- consolidating memories
- validating conflicts

Temporary retention is acceptable.

Current direction:

- keep raw sent-text evidence for about a week
- lazily clean it up
- keep durable memories longer than raw evidence

## Conflict Handling

Memories can change over time.

Example:

- older evidence suggests no greeting
- newer evidence suggests adding a brief personalized greeting

The system should support:

- reinforcement
- recency
- conflict detection
- stale memory handling

Likely fields later:

- `timesSeen`
- `lastSeenAt`
- `confidence`
- `state`

## Immediate Task List

### Phase 1: Simplify Memory Shape

- remove `title + content` split
- keep one canonical memory `content`
- update uniqueness and formatting

### Phase 2: Clean Up Taxonomy

- narrow or replace `STYLE`
- introduce clearer conceptual types: `fact`, `preference`, `procedure`
- stop storing playbooks as generic style

### Phase 3: Add Evidence Graduation Rules

- do not treat every extracted item as a durable prompt memory
- define promotion rules by kind
- allow fast promotion for very high-confidence preference signals
- require stronger reinforcement for broader facts/procedures

### Phase 4: Build Memory Consolidation

- merge near-duplicate memories
- rebuild learned style profile from preference evidence
- weaken or retire stale/conflicted memories

### Phase 5: Build Subagent Memory CAG

- generate a compact per-account tag index
- allow progressive disclosure by tags
- allow optional free-form search
- let the subagent extract relevant items before handing context to the main drafter

### Phase 6: Improve Analysis and Evals

- log repeated residual draft mistakes
- separate runtime memory from offline improvement signals
- generate eval cases from repeated failure modes

## Key Design Rule

The memory system is a residual improvement layer.

Search, inbox context, relationships, and KB retrieval should continue to do most of the factual heavy lifting.
Memory should capture what repeatedly goes wrong or what the user reliably corrects.
